sentences: Andrew Robert Wade (born August 4, 1984) is an American recording engineer and music producer.

section: == Early years and A Wish for Marilynne (2002–2006) ==

sentences: Early years and A Wish for Marilynne (2002–2006) ==
section: == Early years and A Wish for Marilynne (2002–2006) ==

sentences: In August 2002, Wade started playing guitar and singing lead vocals in Christian rock/emo band A Wish for Marilynne.
section: == Early years and A Wish for Marilynne (2002–2006) ==

sentences: By September 2003, the band had written seven songs, three of which made it on to a demo tape, that was recorded four months prior.
section: == Early years and A Wish for Marilynne (2002–2006) ==

sentences: In an interview with the Ocala Star-Banner the band said that once they had ten songs they were going to start recording, and Wade said "it's (going to) be a lot better than the demo."
section: == Early years and A Wish for Marilynne (2002–2006) ==

sentences: By this point, the group had performed a total of twelve shows.
section: == Early years and A Wish for Marilynne (2002–2006) ==

sentences: The band started recording their album, Poetic Chaos, at Wade's The Wade Studio on May 10, 2004, with a projected release date of June.
section: == Early years and A Wish for Marilynne (2002–2006) ==

sentences: In June, the band were booking dates for a summer tour with bands A Midnight and May and There for Tomorrow.
section: == Early years and A Wish for Marilynne (2002–2006) ==

sentences: The band performed at Easy Street in Ocala, Florida on June 3 with bands Starting Over and A Day to Remember, and at The Masquerade in Ocala, Florida on June 20 with bands Inkblot (Cornerstone '04), Vindicated Youth, and Knox Overstreet.
section: == Early years and A Wish for Marilynne (2002–2006) ==

sentences: In August, the band said on their website that the album would "be ready by the end of summer".
section: == Early years and A Wish for Marilynne (2002–2006) ==

sentences: Song songs were uploaded to the band's PureVolume account.
section: == Early years and A Wish for Marilynne (2002–2006) ==

sentences: In December, the band announced recording had finished and release was soon to follow.
section: == Early years and A Wish for Marilynne (2002–2006) ==

sentences: In February 2005, the band announced that the album, Poetic Chaos, was to be released on March 18.
section: == Early years and A Wish for Marilynne (2002–2006) ==

sentences: A release show was held Central Christian Church on the same day, featuring bands There For Tomorrow, A Day to Remember, and Starting Over.
section: == Early years and A Wish for Marilynne (2002–2006) ==

sentences: Song previews were also made available on the band's MySpace account.

sentences: Record producer (2004–present)

By October 2004, The Wade Studio's equipment was the following: Soundcraft Spirit E8 Mixer, Multicom Pro XL - compressor/limiter/gate, Soundtech ST31EQ - 31 band equalizer, Creative I-Trigue L3500 100 watt monitoring system, Edirol MA-10ABK Stereo Powered Monitors, a variety of plugins, Studiologic velocity-sensitive MIDI controller, Cad M177 condenser mic, Nady SCM900 condenser mic, Shure SM57, 3 CAD TSM411 dynamic drum mics, pair of Apex 170 condenser mics, and a CAD KBM412 large-diameter dynamic kick mic.
Wade, along with Drew Russ, under the name Manly Masculine Men recorded the theme song, "Making History", for the web series that was to support A Day to Remember's Common Courtesy (2013) album.
"Making History" was released a single, under the name Manly Masculine Men on October 25.
Wade taught an online course in guitar production for creativeLIVE on both October 22 and 23.
